f> included in ''[[Life of Pythagoras]] (De Vita Pythagorica)'', written by [[Iamblichus]]. Abrotelia's father was [[Abroteles of Tarentum]] and she is thought to have been born in [[Tarentum (Campus Martius)|Tarentum]].<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Ogilvie|editor1-first=Marilyn|editor2-last=Harvey|editor2-first=Joy|chapter=Abrotelia (fl. 5th century B.C.E.)|title=Biographical Dictionary of Women in Science: Pioneering Lives From Ancient Times to the Mid-20th Century|date=2000|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=0-415-92040-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rUCUAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA10&ots=7dNZy3KejY&dq=Abrotelia&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=10}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Wichmann|first1=Christian August|title=Geschichte berühmter Frauenzimmer: Nach alphabetischer Ordnung aus alten und neuen in- und ausländischen Geschicht-Sammlungen und Wörterbüchern zusammen getragen, Volume 1|chapter=Abrotelia|date=1772|publisher=Böhm|page=12|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0cI5AAAAcAAJ&lpg=PA11&ots=2HR_xmZn1c&dq=Abrotelia&pg=PA12#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Iamblichus cited Abrotelia as one of the illustrious female Phytagorean philosophers, although her name was among the nine who were listed with names of their husbands or male family members.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reading 1 Corinthians with Philosophically Educated Women|last=Barnes|first=Nathan|publisher=Pickwick Publications|year=2014|isbn=9781620325728|location=Eugene, OR|pages=89}}</ref> Some scholars such as Ethel Kersey identified Abrotelia as one of those who wrote or taught in traditional philosophical fields such as [[metaphysics]], [[logic]], and [[aesthetics]], among others.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Philosophy: A Guide to the Reference Literature|last=Bynagle|first=Hans Edward|publisher=Libraries Unlimited|year=2006|isbn=1563089548|location=Westport, CT|pages=104}}</ref> She is also listed in [[Gilles Ménage]]'s ''Historia Mulierum Philosopharum, which'' showed the Phytagorean school as the sect with the most number of female philosophers, with its adherents greater than the Platonic sect.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Models of the History of Philosophy: Volume II: From Cartesian Age to Brucker|last=Santinello|first=Giovanni|last2=Piaia|first2=Gregorio|publisher=Springer Science+Business Media|year=2010|isbn=9789048195060|location=Dordrecht|pages=75}}</ref>
